@node WIN_MAIN "JV-80/Main window"

This is the main window. This is the place where you create, save and load
your patches. When you close this window you also close the whole JV-80 
PlugIn module itself - all windows will be closed automagically. If you 
have any unsaved changes you will get a chance to regret quitting.

@{u}What's in the window@{uu}
The main listview gadget contains your patches. When you select a patch the
patch will be send via the MIDI port to the JV-80. With the string gadget
below you can change the name of the patch. Only the characters that are 
displayable in the JV-80's display can be entered here..

If a patch has been changed it will get a "*" in front of it's name.

The window title shows which Tone you are editing. If you are editing all 4
tones at a time you'll see a "All" after the tone #.

 · Load
     Brings up a filerequester where you can select a patch to load. The
     chosen patch will be loaded into the currently selected patch.
     
     You can also load raw system exclusive dump patch files from
     programs like SysExpert.

 · Save
     Saves the currently selected patch. Brings up a filerequester where
     you can specify the filename. See also @{"Settings window" link PREF}
     
 · New & Load
     Creates a new patch and opens a filrequester where you choose the 
     patch to load.
     
 · Save *
     Saves all the patches that are marked as changed.
     
 · New
     Creates a new patch. The patch will be a copy of the currently 
     selected patch.
     
 · Remove
     Removes the currently selected patch.
     
 · Send
     Sends the currently selected patch to the JV-80. Only useful if you 
     don't use the @{b}real time updating@{ub} feature.
 
 · Receive
     Receives a patch from within the JV-80's user patch bank. The patch
     to receive is determined by the current patch's number.

@{u}How to set the Patch #@{uu}
Double clicking on an entry in the listview will bring up a window where 
you can edit the patch's number. This is the user patch number in 
the JV-80.
 
@endnode


@node PREF "JV-80/Settings window"

The settings window is where you can edit the functionality and look of
the JV-80 PlugIn.

@{u}What's in the window@{uu}

 · Patch Path
     Here you can specify where you want your patches to be. 

 · Patch Bank Path
     Here you can specify where you want your patch banks to be. 

 · File postfix
     The contents of this string gadget will be added to all the files you
     save. Ex. if you have entered @{b}.JV-80@{ub} here and you save a
     patch with the name @{b}MegaBass@{ub} the file will be called
     @{b}MegaBass.JV-80@{ub}.

     [Not implemented yet]
     
 · Unit #
     This is the device unit number of your JV-80. 

 · Expansion modules
     This is the place where you can configure which expansion module you
     have in your JV-80. Press the popup-gadget and a listview
     gadget pops up showing you the available expansion modules. Select a 
     expansion-module by double-clicking on an entry. Now you will be
     able to select the waveforms in the @{" wave window " link WAVE} just as you select
     one of the built-in waveforms.
     
     @{b}Note:@{ub} You'll have to save the settings, quit and restart the JV-80
     module before these changes will have any effect. Sorry about that -
     maybe I'll do something about it later..
     
 · Listview Titles
     With these checkmark gadgets you can change the look of the titles in
     the listview gadgets. You can mix the different text attributes as
     you please. Ex. Bold underline is perfectly okay..
     
       · Show. With this one you can enable or disable the titles.
       · Bold. The titles will be in bold.
       · Italics. The titles will be in bold.
       · Underline. The titles will be underlined.

 · Control Strip
     The control strip is a window where you can open any of the windows
     in this PlugIn. It gives you a fast way to open (or activate) the
     many windows. You can change the look of the window:
     
       · Equal Size Buttons. If checked all the buttons in this window will
         be the same size.
         
       · Horizontal/Vertical. Specifies how you want the layout of the window.

The @{b}Save, Use and Cancel@{ub} buttons acts like in any other preferences window. 
@endnode


@node WIN_PBNK "JV-80/Patch Bank window"

This is the patch bank window. 

@{u}What's in the window@{uu}
The main listview gadget contains your patch bank. In the window's title
bar you can see how many entries in the patch bank that are currently used.

 · @{b}Load Bank@{ub}
     Loads a patch bank from disk. Opens filerequester.
 
 · @{b}Save Bank@{ub}
     Saves a patch bank to disk. Opens a filerequester.
 
 · @{b}Load Patch@{ub}
     Brings up a filerequester where you can select one or more patches 
     to load. The loaded patch will replace the currently active entry.

     If you load more than one patch they will be placed one after
     the other overwriting any existing patches in your bank.
 
 · @{b}Save Patch@{ub}
     Saves the currently selected patches. Brings up a filerequester.

     If only one patch is selected you can specify the file name and 
     destination directory of the patch. If more than one patch is 
     selected you just select destination directory and all the patches 
     will be saved there with their current names as the file name.
 
 · @{b}Store Current@{ub}
     Pressing this button will copy the currently selected patch in the
     @{"Main window" link WIN_MAIN} to the currently selected entry in this, the patch bank window.
 
 · @{b}Remove@{ub}
     Removes the currently selected patch(es). If more than one patch
     is selected a confirmation requester pops-up enabling you to abort
     the removal.
 
 · @{b}Send@{ub}
     Pressing this button will send the whole patch bank to the JV-80.
     Only the used entries will be send thus saving transfer time.
     
 · @{b}Receive@{ub}
     Pressing this button opens a window where you enter the desired range
     of patches to receive from the user patch memory in the JV-80. The 
     default is all the user patches in the JV-80. Hitting the okay button
     will start the transfer.

@{u}Drag'n'drop@{uu}
You can use drag'n'drop to rearrange the order of the patches in the listview.
You can also drag patches from the main window to the patch bank.

@{u}Renaming of patches@{uu}
You can rename a patch in the patch bank by double-clicking on the patch
you want to rename. A window pops up where you can type the new name. Double-
clicking on an empty entry has no effect. 

Instead of double-clicking you can also press <RETURN> (well, this depends on
how your MUI is set up)
 
@endnode

@node PCMN "JV-80/Patch Common window"

In this window you can change common patch parameters.

Note that you can also change the patch name in the @{" main window " link MAIN}

@endnode

@node PEFX "JV-80/Patch Effects window"

@endnode

@node TCTR "JV-80/Tone Control window"

@endnode

@node WAVE "JV-80/Wave window"

In the Wave window you can edit wave-parameters for a Tone.

If you have a expansion board in your JV-80 you must
specify which one. This is done in the @{" settings window " link PREF}

@endnode

@node LFO "JV-80/LFO window"

This is the window where you control the two LFO's. Low Frequency Oscillators.

@endnode

@node PITC "JV-80/Pitch window"

This is the pitch window where you edit parameters that controls the 
pitch. The big gadget at the bottom controls the pitch @{" envelope " link ENVELOPE}

@endnode

@node TVF "JV-80/TVF window"

This is the TVF window where you edit parameters that controls the 
TVF. The big gadget at the bottom controls the @{" envelope " link ENVELOPE}

@endnode

@node TVA "JV-80/TVA window"

This is the TVA window where you edit parameters that controls the 
TVA. The big gadget at the bottom controls the @{" envelope " link ENVELOPE}

@endnode

